{"id":"2111.03765","submitter":"Taku Moriyama","authors":"Taku Moriyama","title":"Parametric and nonparametric probability distribution estimators of\n  sample maximum","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.ST stat.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Extreme value theory has constructed asymptotic properties of the sample\nmaximum under some parametric assumptions. This study concerns probability\ndistribution estimation of the sample maximum. The traditional approach is\nparametric fitting to the limiting distribution - the generalized extreme value\ndistribution; however, the model in finite cases is misspecified to a certain\nextent. We propose a plug-in type of nonparametric estimator that does not need\nmodel specification. Asymptotic properties of the distribution estimator are\nderived. The numerical performances of the parametric estimator and the\nnonparametric estimator are compared in this study. A simulation experiment\ndemonstrates the obtained asymptotic convergence rates and clarifies the\ninfluence of misspecification in the context of probability distribution\nestimation.\n  This study assumes that the underlying distribution of the original sample\nbelongs to one of the Hall class, the Weibull class and the bounded class,\nwhose types of the limiting distributions are all different: the Frechet,\nGumbel and Weibull. It is proven that the convergence rate of the parametric\nfitting estimator depends on both the tail index and the second-order parameter\nand gets slow as the tail index tends to zero. The simulation results are\ngenerally consistent with the obtained convergence rates. Finally, we report\ntwo real case studies: the Potomac River peak stream flow (cfs) data and the\nDanish Fire Insurance data.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 6 Nov 2021 01:01:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 29 Dec 2021 04:31:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created